od items and snack foods loaded with sugar, salt, and fat? What is the nutritional profile of the federal meals? How well are they reaching students who need them? Opening a window onto our culture as a whole, Poppendieck reveals the forces--the financial troubles of schools, the commercialization of childhood, the reliance on market models--that are determining how lunch is served. She concludes with a sweeping vision for change: fresh, healthy food for all children as a regular part of their school day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChildrenxNutritionzUnited States. 0aNational school lunch program. 0aSchool breakfast programszUnited States. 0aSchool childrenxFoodzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamerica.  abehind the scenes.  acalifornia.  achildrens lunches.  acomprehensive account.  aenvironmental sustainability.  afast food.  afederal meals.  afood and culture.  afood culture.  afood history.  afood policies.  afood politics.  afood provision.  afood taste.  amultiple perspectives.  anonfiction.  anutrition and health.  apolitical.  aregulated meals.  asalty food.  aschool food.  aschool kitchens.  aschool lunches.  asocial change.  asocial science.  astudents and parents.  asugar and fat.  asustainable food.  athought provoking.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024370540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094441140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944411423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944411/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter